"Aoyama M., Goto H., Kamiya H., Kaneko I., Kawae S., Kodama H., Konishi Y., Kusumoto K.-I., Miura H., Moriyama E., Murakami K., Nakano T., Nozaki F., Sasano D., Shimizu T., Suzuki H., Takatsuki Y., Toriyama A.","Marine biogeochemical response to a rapid warming in the main stream of the Kuroshio in the western North Pacific",2008,"Fisheries Oceanography","17","3",,"206","218",,,10.1111/j.1365-2419.2008.00473.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-42449121724&partnerID=40&md5=c6f79f04d8c9b106fb303519568e8ac2","Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Kagoshima Local Meteorological Observatory, 4-1 Higashi-Korimoto, Kagoshima 890-0068, Japan; Marine Division, Climate and Marine Department, Japan Meteorological Agency, 1-3-4 Otemachi, Chiyodaku, Tokyo 100-8122, Japan; Nagasaki Marine Observatory, Japan Meteorological Agency, 11-51 Minami-yamate-Machi, Nagasaki 850-0931, Japan; Maizuru Marine Observatory, Maizuru Harbor Office Building, 901 Shimohukui, Maizuru, Kyoto 624-0946, Japan; Sapporo District Meteorological Observatory, 18-2 Kita, 2Jo Nishi, Chuo-ku, Sapporo, Hokkaido 060-0002, Japan; Hakodate Marine Observatory, 3-4-4 Mihara, Hakodate, Hokkaido 041-0806, Japan","Aoyama, M., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Goto, H., Kagoshima Local Meteorological Observatory, 4-1 Higashi-Korimoto, Kagoshima 890-0068, Japan; Kamiya, H., Marine Division, Climate and Marine Department, Japan Meteorological Agency, 1-3-4 Otemachi, Chiyodaku, Tokyo 100-8122, Japan; Kaneko, I., Marine Division, Climate and Marine Department, Japan Meteorological Agency, 1-3-4 Otemachi, Chiyodaku, Tokyo 100-8122, Japan; Kawae, S., Nagasaki Marine Observatory, Japan Meteorological Agency, 11-51 Minami-yamate-Machi, Nagasaki 850-0931, Japan; Kodama, H., Sapporo District Meteorological Observatory, 18-2 Kita, 2Jo Nishi, Chuo-ku, Sapporo, Hokkaido 060-0002, Japan; Konishi, Y., Maizuru Marine Observatory, Maizuru Harbor Office Building, 901 Shimohukui, Maizuru, Kyoto 624-0946, Japan; Kusumoto, K.-I., Marine Division, Climate and Marine Department, Japan Meteorological Agency, 1-3-4 Otemachi, Chiyodaku, Tokyo 100-8122, Japan; Miura, H., Hakodate Marine Observatory, 3-4-4 Mihara, Hakodate, Hokkaido 041-0806, Japan; Moriyama, E., Maizuru Marine Observatory, Maizuru Harbor Office Building, 901 Shimohukui, Maizuru, Kyoto 624-0946, Japan; Murakami, K., Nagasaki Marine Observatory, Japan Meteorological Agency, 11-51 Minami-yamate-Machi, Nagasaki 850-0931, Japan; Nakano, T., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Nozaki, F., Marine Division, Climate and Marine Department, Japan Meteorological Agency, 1-3-4 Otemachi, Chiyodaku, Tokyo 100-8122, Japan; Sasano, D., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Shimizu, T., Nagasaki Marine Observatory, Japan Meteorological Agency, 11-51 Minami-yamate-Machi, Nagasaki 850-0931, Japan; Suzuki, H., Nagasaki Marine Observatory, Japan Meteorological Agency, 11-51 Minami-yamate-Machi, Nagasaki 850-0931, Japan; Takatsuki, Y., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Toriyama, A., Maizuru Marine Observatory, Maizuru Harbor Office Building, 901 Shimohukui, Maizuru, Kyoto 624-0946, Japan","Impact of climate change on marine biogeochemical parameters and ecosystem is one of the important issues of our environment. Direct evidence of marine pelagic ecosystem changes is found with warming of sea water and sea-level rise in the main stream of the Kuroshio in the East China Sea and the western North Pacific during these three decades based on the analysis of long-term comprehensive hydrographic observations. In terms of annual mean, the warming rate of surface air temperature and sea surface temperature ranged from 0.15 to 0.21°C per decade in and around the main stream of the Kuroshio in the East China Sea, which exceed the global mean warming rate of 0.128 ± 0.026°C per decade during the period from 1956 to 2005 reported in IPCC 2007. One of the features in this rapid warming region is an increase of number of Pterosagitta draco, a cosmopolitan warm-water zooplankton. Biogeochemical parameters, such as wet weight of zooplankton, plant pigment and nutrients concentration in the upper 200 m have been decreasing while dissolved oxygen content and seawater temperature have been increasing in the upper 200 m in the main stream of the Kuroshio in the East China Sea. These observed linear trends of the biogeochemical parameters would be foresights for temperate oceans in the future. © 2008 The Authors.","Biogeochemical change; Climate change; Global warming; Kuroshio; North Pacific","biogeochemistry; climate change; climate effect; ecosystem response; environmental change; global warming; population growth; sea level change; sea surface temperature; zooplankton; East China Sea; Kuroshio Region; Pacific Ocean; Pterosagitta draco",,,,,,"Aoyama, M., Joyce, T.M., Kawano, T., Takatsuki, Y., Standard seawater comparison up to P129 (2002) Deep-Sea Res. I, 49, pp. 1103-1114; Armstrong, F.A.J., Stearns, C.R., Strickland, J.D.H., The measurement of upwelling and subsequent biological processes by means of the TechniconTM AutoanalyzerTM and associated equipment (1967) Deep-Sea Res., 14, pp. 381-389; Beaugrand, G., Philip, C.R., Frederic, I., Alistair, L.J., Martin, E., Reorganization of North Atlantic Marine copepod biodiversity and climate (2002) Science, 296, pp. 1692-1694; Bieri, R., The distribution of the planktonic Chaetognatha in the Pacific and their relationship to the water masses (1959) Limnol. Oceanogr., 4, pp. 1-28; Bopp, L., Le Quéré, C., Heimann, M., Manning, A.C., Monfray, P., Climate-induced oceanic oxygen fluxes: Implications for the contemporary carbon budget (2002) Glob Biogeoch Cyc., 16, pp. 6-1; Carpenter, J.H., The Chesapeake Bay Institute technique for the Winkler dissolve